---

SITUATION SUMMARY

At approximately 09:12 UTC today, finance user k.thornton fell victim to a
credential phishing attack via a spoofed DocuSign email. The attacker used the
harvested credentials to access k.thornton's O365 account, bypassing MFA via
a legacy auth exemption that was still active on the account.

Between 09:22 and 09:26 UTC, the attacker downloaded approximately 40MB of
data from SharePoint (Finance forecasts, HR compensation data, vendor contracts)
and set up an inbox forwarding rule to an external Proton Mail address.

The attacker then sent wire transfer requests from k.thornton's account to
accounts payable contacts, requesting $47,500 to an external bank account.
The wire has NOT been processed — AP clerk p.osei identified the request as
suspicious and contacted k.thornton directly.

Account was disabled and session revoked at 10:58 UTC. Containment is holding.
No lateral movement detected at this time.

---

IMMEDIATE ACTIONS TAKEN

- k.thornton account session revoked and account disabled (10:58 UTC)
- Inbox forwarding rule deleted (11:05 UTC)
- Wire transfer request cancelled — confirmed with Finance (11:15 UTC)
- MFA enforced on k.thornton retroactively
- IT reviewing all other legacy auth exemptions (4 additional accounts identified)

---

OPEN RISK ITEMS

1. DATA EXFILTRATION: ~40MB of sensitive data (finance, HR, vendor) confirmed
   downloaded. Contents include EU employee salary data — GDPR assessment required.
   Legal has been notified. 72-hour GDPR clock starts from 13:00 UTC today.

2. EMAIL FORWARDING: 3 emails confirmed forwarded to external address before
   rule was deleted. Contents: HR internal thread, vendor invoice, client email.

3. LEGACY AUTH EXPOSURE: 4 additional accounts with legacy auth exemptions
   identified. None compromised but all at elevated risk. Remediation in progress.

4. WIRE FRAUD: $47,500 wire request sent to AP. Payment blocked. No financial
   loss at this time — monitoring for further attempts.

---

CISO ACTION REQUIRED

Please confirm receipt and approve external notification to ICO (GDPR Art. 33).
